"1239–Male":"1239–Deceased","1242–Male":"1242–Deceased","1180–1251":"1180–1251","1180–1220":"1180–1220","1220":"1220","1242":"1242","1251":"1251","1272":"1272","1293":"1293","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1180":"1180","1239":"1239","1216":"1216","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","1236":"1236","about 1239":"about 1239","1224":"1224","1212":"1212","about 1237":"about 1237","before 1251":"before 1251","1306":"1306","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Little Salkeld, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Little Salkeld, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom","Little Salkeld, Cumberland, England":"Little Salkeld, Cumberland, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Salkeld","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from Salkeld (Cumberland), probably from Old English <i>salh</i> ‘willow, sallow’ + <i>hylte</i> ‘wood’, though the final element may have been confused with Old Norse <i>kelda</i> ‘spring, marshy place’. Alternatively, the final element may be an Old English <i>hilde</i>, a variant of <i>helde</i> ‘slope’. This surname has been present (though never common) in Ireland for centuries."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":3,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":12,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":47,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":78,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas Salkeld was born in 1212, in Yorkshire, England, his father, Robert Salkeld, was 32 and his mother, Alice Huddlesceugh